Azam, who played a short-arm jab towards deep midwicket, was guilty of staying put and admiring his shot even as Malik completed the single. It should have been two, and so he turned to come back, only to see Azam put his hand out late. Another second and he could have been run out at the striker's end

commentary: Benn to Shoaib Malik, SIX runs make that a hat-trick. Benn doesn't learn from his mistakes. Angles it in to the right-hander again and gives a lot of flight. Malik was ready for it and comes down the track and gets it over deep midwicket. This is the biggest of the three and the ball has actually gone out of the stadium to the roads. 103 metres! A fan jumps across and braves the traffic to fetch the ball. Kudos to him!

commentary: Narine to Shoaib Malik, OUT That should count as a bonus wicket, against the run of play. Malik can't believe what he's just done. Shapes to cut, the intention was right, but the execution came a cropper as he skewed a simple catch to Darren Bravo at backward point. For a moment, no one even reacted, such was the mood in the West Indies camp after coming under Malik's sustained attack. This should give them some relief. Narine may have just got the ball to bounce a little more on that occasion as a result of which the ball flew off a thick outside edge.

commentary: CR Brathwaite to Sarfraz Ahmed, 1 leg bye gets down to sweep and the ball hits him on the pad. The umpire doesn't give it and West Indies ask for a review. It was very full and Sarfaraz goes down and tries to sweep. But the ball pings him on the back leg before running away fine on the leg side. The question is whether there was any bat or glove involved. This might be a very good review, as there doesn't seem to be any bat or glove involved. Backfoot is in front of leg stump. Hawk-eye shows that it is missing the stumps, but that was not a bad review at all. Ramdin had asked for it and it isn't easy to pick from that angle

commentary: Shoaib Malik to KC Brathwaite, OUT what a waste of a wicket. It was pushed a long way across and Brathwaite makes room and slaps it away. He sets off for a run but point moves quickly to his right and picks it up. He wanted to fire the throw at the bowler's end but changes his mind and hurls a good throw at the wicketkeeper's end. Brathwaite is sent back and Sarfraz collects it cleanly and whips the bails off. Brathwaite is nowhere to be seen, kicks the turf as he walks off

commentary: Imad Wasim to Samuels, no run it's a slightly short delivery and Samuels comes forward with a big backlift before making a late adjustment and tries to defend . He is rapped on the pads and there is an appeal for lbw. Azhar consults with Imad before going for the review. Samuels defended it with his bat very close to pad, but Imad is pretty certain there was no bat. He was a long way down the track. Hawkeye shows that the ball would have clipped the top of leg stumps. Less than 50 percent of the ball hitting, so the on-field umpire's call stays

commentary: Imad Wasim to Samuels, SIX runs Rizwan palms that over the fence at deep midwicket. Samuels didn't get hold of that slog whatsoever, only managed a top edge that should have been taken by the boundary rider. Rizwan was in a couple of paces to make it difficult. Had he been at the ropes, it would have been a regulation catch. No excuses nevertheless, should have been taken. Tried to reverse cup that. Also, the momentum was taking him backwards, which is much more difficult

commentary: Wahab Riaz to Samuels, OUT no, it doesn't because Wahab has cleaned him up with pace. That was a short of length delivery on middle at 146 kph, it kept a touch low as well, but Samuels was late on it and ended up playing it onto the stumps. Valiant knock, but you got the feeling one good ball was all that was needed at this stage, especially with him swinging come hell or high water. Relief for Pakistan
